[[File:Valent ae3 316.gif|thumb|An AE3 coin of [[Valens]].]]
The '''Constantinian bronzes''' were a series of [[bronze]] [[coin]]s introduced in the [[Roman Empire]] in the middle of the [[4th century]]. The specific denominations are unclear and debated by historians and [[numismatist]]s. They are referred to as AE1, AE2, AE3, and AE4, with the former being the largest (near 27 mm) and the latter the smallest (averaging 15 mm) in diameter:

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;" border="1" 
|-
! AE1 !! AE2 !! AE3 !! AE4
|-
|  over 25&nbsp;mm || 21 – 25&nbsp;mm  ||  17 – 21&nbsp;mm ||  under 17&nbsp;mm 
|}

In November 2013, the largest [[hoard]] of [[Constantine the Great|Constantinian]] bronze coins was discovered in [[Devon]], [[England]]. The [[Seaton Down Hoard]] consists of 22,000 coins, mostly Constantinian bronzes.<ref>[http://www.sundaypost.com/that-s-life/memories/large-roman-coin-hoard-unearthed-1.597455 Large Roman coin hoard unearthed]</ref>

