{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site | WHS = Hidden Christian Sites in the Nagasaki Region | Image = Oura Tenshudo Temple, Nagasaki 2014.jpg | Caption = Ōura Cathedral | Location = [[Nagasaki Prefecture|Nagasaki]] and [[Kumamoto Prefecture|Kumamoto]], Japan | Criteria = Cultural: iii | ID = 1495 | Year = 2018 | Area = 5,566.55 ha | Buffer_zone = 12,252.52 ha | Coordinates = {{coord|32.734106|129.870236}} | locmapin = Japan }} '''Hidden Christian Sites in the Nagasaki Region''' ({{lang-ja|長崎と天草地方の潜伏キリシタン関連遺産}}) is a group of twelve sites in [[Nagasaki Prefecture]] and [[Kumamoto Prefecture]] relating to the history of [[Christianity in Japan]]. The Nagasaki churches are unique in the sense that each tells a story about the revival of Christianity after a long period of official suppression.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5096/ |title=Churches and Christian Sites in Nagasaki |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=21 Sep 2011}}</ref>
Proposed jointly in 2007 for inscription on the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage List]] under criteria [[World Heritage Site#Cultural criteria|ii, iii, iv, v, and vi]], the submission named at the time '''Churches and Christian Sites in Nagasaki''' on the [[World Heritage Site#Nominating process|Tentative List]], was recognized on January 30, 2018 as a World Heritage Site.
The initial nomination included 26 sites; however, after reconsideration the Nagasaki Prefecture reduced the monuments to 13 sites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5096/ |title=Churches and Christian Sites in Nagasaki |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=}}; {{cite web |url=http://www.pref.nagasaki.jp/s_isan/en/assets/|title=Outline of Churches and Christian Sites |publisher=[[Nagasaki Prefecture]] |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> Twelve sites were recognized. Controversies over the Hidden Christian Sites in the Nagasaki Region have been widely discussed in the academic literature.<ref>http://www.drustvo-antropologov.si/AN/PDF/2017_3/Anthropological_Notebooks_XIII_3_Delakorda.pdf</ref>
==Christianity in Japan== {{main|History of Roman Catholicism in Japan|Kirishitan|Kakure Kirishitan}}
[[Christianity]] arrived in [[Japan]] in 1549 with the [[Jesuit]] missionary [[Francis Xavier]]. Fanning out from [[Nagasaki]], the new faith won many converts, including a number of ''[[daimyō]]s''. [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] then [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] persecuted those professing to be Christian. After the [[Shimabara Rebellion]] of 1637–1638, the official repression of Christian practices was combined with a [[Sakoku|policy of national seclusion]] that lasted over two centuries. With the [[Opening of Japan#Commodore Perry .281853–54.29|advent of Western powers and reopening of Japan]] in the 1850s and the reforms of the [[Meiji Restoration]], missionary activity was renewed and a number of [[Kakure Kirishitan|Hidden Christians]] resurfaced. [[Ōura Cathedral]] of 1864 is the first of the churches built in subsequent years.<ref>{{cite book |title=Meiji Revisited: The Sites of Victorian Japan |author=Finn, Dallas |publisher=[[Weatherhill]] |year=1995 |ISBN=0-8348-0288-0 |pages=12f}}</ref>
